// Reject fixture: out_of_scope_type_param — a type-parameter name is in scope
// only for the item that declares it. `id` declares `<T>`, so `T` is a valid
// annotation inside `id`. `bad` declares no type params, so its `x: T` names a
// type that does not exist in `bad`'s scope. The checker reports it at the
// annotation with `unknown type `T``, rather than silently exempting it because
// some *other* function happens to declare a `T` and leaking an opaque
// `Ty::named("T")` that only surfaces downstream as `E_MIR: unknown type` at
// the MIR boundary.
//
// Guards against a too-broad exemption: proving a source annotation valid must
// be scope-aware, not satisfied by any type-param name declared program-wide.
//
// Harness verb: hew check
// Expected: rejected with `unknown type `T`` at `bad`'s parameter annotation.
fn id<T>(x: T) -> T { x }

fn bad(x: T) -> i64 { 0 }

fn main() -> i64 { id(5) }
